    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Phaius tahitensis are made from its roots and include tea, which is a liquid solution prepared by infusing the root in hot water, infusion, a process of steeping the root in cold water, tincture, a concentrated liquid extract of the root, salve, a topical application of the root's extract in a fatty base to soothe skin issues, and decoction, a liquid solution made by boiling the root in water to release its bioactive compounds. Phaius tahitensis is used due to its reported anti-inflammatory, antimicrobial, and antioxidant properties. These properties are attributed to the presence of bioactive compounds such as flavonoids, phenolic acids, and saponins in the root. The preparations of Phaius tahitensis are used to treat various health conditions, including wounds, skin infections, and digestive issues. The efficacy of these preparations is supported by traditional use and some scientific studies, although further research is needed to fully understand their effects.",
